<subSubSection pageId="19" pageNumber="20" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1437,253,1119]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,326,413,439]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Santos, 2007" authorityName="Santos" authorityYear="2007" box="[334,534,413,438]" class="Arachnida" family="Pisauridae" genus="Architis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="altamira" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[334,534,413,438]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Architis altamira</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[542,636,413,439]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[542,636,413,439]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
is close to 
<taxonomicName authority="Santos, 2007" authorityName="Santos" authorityYear="2007" box="[769,903,413,438]" class="Arachnida" family="Pisauridae" genus="Architis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="comaina" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[769,903,413,438]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">A. comaina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[911,1005,413,439]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[911,1005,413,439]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Carico" authorityYear="1981" box="[1063,1192,413,438]" class="Arachnida" family="Pisauridae" genus="Architis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ikuruwa">
<emphasis box="[1063,1192,413,438]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">A. ikuruwa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with which it shares the epigynal MF which is appressed under the LL (
<figureCitation box="[762,859,453,479]" captionStart="FIGURES 7" captionStartId="17.[151,269,1595,1619]" captionTargetBox="[300,1292,190,1566]" captionTargetId="figure-143@17.[259,1329,134,1593]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURES 7A–D. Architis comaina sp. nov. A, male pedipalpus, ventral view; B, male pedipalpus, lateral view; C, female epigynum, ventral view; D, female internal genitalia, dorsal view. Scale bars: A–B, 0.2 mm; C–D, 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5097193" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5097193/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Figs 7C</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[873,946,453,479]" captionStart="FIGURES 8" captionStartId="18.[151,269,1869,1893]" captionTargetBox="[196,1393,553,1834]" captionTargetId="figure-209@18.[144,1443,474,1907]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURES 8A–F. Architis spp. A–B, A. ikuruwa Carico: A, female epigynum, ventral view; B, female internal genitalia, dorsal view. C–D, A. altamira sp. nov.: C, female epigynum, ventral view; D, female internal genitalia, dorsal view. E–F, A. dianasilvae sp. nov.: E, female epigynum, ventral view; F, female internal genitalia, dorsal view. Arrows point to the copulatory opening. Scale bars: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5097197" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5097197/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">8A, C</figureCitation>
) and the CD which is encapsulated in an interior fold of the epigynal wall (
<figureCitation box="[550,647,493,519]" captionStart="FIGURES 7" captionStartId="17.[151,269,1595,1619]" captionTargetBox="[300,1292,190,1566]" captionTargetId="figure-143@17.[259,1329,134,1593]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURES 7A–D. Architis comaina sp. nov. A, male pedipalpus, ventral view; B, male pedipalpus, lateral view; C, female epigynum, ventral view; D, female internal genitalia, dorsal view. Scale bars: A–B, 0.2 mm; C–D, 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5097193" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5097193/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Figs 7D</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[660,734,493,519]" captionStart="FIGURES 8" captionStartId="18.[151,269,1869,1893]" captionTargetBox="[196,1393,553,1834]" captionTargetId="figure-209@18.[144,1443,474,1907]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURES 8A–F. Architis spp. A–B, A. ikuruwa Carico: A, female epigynum, ventral view; B, female internal genitalia, dorsal view. C–D, A. altamira sp. nov.: C, female epigynum, ventral view; D, female internal genitalia, dorsal view. E–F, A. dianasilvae sp. nov.: E, female epigynum, ventral view; F, female internal genitalia, dorsal view. Arrows point to the copulatory opening. Scale bars: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5097197" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5097197/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">8B, D</figureCitation>
). It can be differentiated from these species by the presence of an irregularly shaped, sclerotised case encapsulating the CD close to the stalk of each spermatheca and the presence of a pair of cuticular flaps of the internal genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[860,954,573,599]" captionStart="FIGURES 8" captionStartId="18.[151,269,1869,1893]" captionTargetBox="[196,1393,553,1834]" captionTargetId="figure-209@18.[144,1443,474,1907]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURES 8A–F. Architis spp. A–B, A. ikuruwa Carico: A, female epigynum, ventral view; B, female internal genitalia, dorsal view. C–D, A. altamira sp. nov.: C, female epigynum, ventral view; D, female internal genitalia, dorsal view. E–F, A. dianasilvae sp. nov.: E, female epigynum, ventral view; F, female internal genitalia, dorsal view. Arrows point to the copulatory opening. Scale bars: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5097197" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5097197/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Fig. 8D</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="19" pageNumber="20" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1437,253,1119]" box="[198,343,613,639]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,343,613,639]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Description</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1437,253,1119]" box="[199,400,653,679]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,262,653,679]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Male</emphasis>
. Unknown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1437,253,1119]" box="[199,917,693,719]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,290,693,719]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Female</emphasis>
(
<materialsCitation box="[305,917,693,719]" collectorName="Castelo dos Sonhos" country="Brazil" location="Brazil" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" specimenCount="1" typeStatus="holotype">
based on 
<typeStatus box="[418,521,693,719]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">holotype</typeStatus>
from 
<collectorName box="[592,824,693,719]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Castelo dos Sonhos</collectorName>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[836,909,693,719]" name="Brazil" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Brazil</collectingCountry>
)
</materialsCitation>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1437,253,1119]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
Carapace reddish-brown, dark brown medially and marginally. Anterior eye row procurved, lateral eyes strongly projected ventrally and almost twice as large as medians. Posterior eyes of similar size. Clypeus cream-coloured, chelicerae reddish-brown. Eye sizes and arrangement as in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Carico. A" authorityYear="1981" box="[1039,1177,813,838]" class="Arachnida" family="Pisauridae" genus="Architis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cymatilis">
<emphasis box="[1039,1177,813,838]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">A. cymatilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see 
<bibRefCitation author="Carico, J. E." box="[1237,1385,813,839]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" pagination="140 - 153" refId="ref25013" refString="Carico, J. E. (1981) The Neotropical spider genera Architis and Staberius (Pisauridae). Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History, 170, 140 - 153." type="journal article" year="1981">Carico 1981</bibRefCitation>
; fig. 11). Sternum cream-coloured, with marginal brown spots at the base of coxae. Labium and endites reddishbrown. Pedipalpi and legs reddish-brown. Opisthosoma gray dorsally, with dark spots. Venter and sides cream-coloured, with dark spots. Spinnerets reddish-brown. Total length 3.2; carapace 1.7 long, 1.4 wide. Tibia I length 3.1, II 3.0, III 2.2, IV 2.7. Opisthosoma 1.5 long, 2.5 wide. LL of epigynum with a pair of anterior, laterally directed small hoods covering copulatory openings (
<figureCitation box="[924,1016,1013,1039]" captionStart="FIGURES 8" captionStartId="18.[151,269,1869,1893]" captionTargetBox="[196,1393,553,1834]" captionTargetId="figure-209@18.[144,1443,474,1907]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURES 8A–F. Architis spp. A–B, A. ikuruwa Carico: A, female epigynum, ventral view; B, female internal genitalia, dorsal view. C–D, A. altamira sp. nov.: C, female epigynum, ventral view; D, female internal genitalia, dorsal view. E–F, A. dianasilvae sp. nov.: E, female epigynum, ventral view; F, female internal genitalia, dorsal view. Arrows point to the copulatory opening. Scale bars: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5097197" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5097197/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Fig. 8C</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1437,253,1119]" box="[199,959,1053,1079]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,324,1053,1079]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Variation.</emphasis>
Female 
<typeStatus box="[425,529,1053,1079]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">paratype</typeStatus>
, total length 3.1, carapace width 1.6.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
